NRG BUSINESS MARKETING LLC RATE SCHEDULE FERC NO. 1 Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service NRG Business Marketing LLC (“NBM”) provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service (“Reactive Supply Service”) from the Chalk Point generation facility (“Facility”) within the Potomac Electric Power Company zone under the operational control of PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. This Rate Schedule FERC No. 1 sets forth NBM’s revenue requirement for Reactive Supply Service from the Facility for the unit set forth below. This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. NBM’s monthly fixed revenue requirement consists of the charge for the Facility’s unit specified below.
REVENUE REQUIREMENT:
Chalk Point Unit Monthly Revenue Requirement SMECO CT $7,815.19 Total Monthly Revenue Requirement $7,815.19 Total Annual (Total Monthly x 12) $93,782.28
PARTIAL MONTH REVENUE REQUIREMENT: When a unit deactivation date (“Unit Deactivation Date”) is other than the first day of the month, the revenue requirement shall be a blended revenue requirement for the month of service in which the deactivation occurred as follows: the sum of (i) the total monthly revenue requirement prior to the rate change divided by the number of days in the month of the deactivation, with the quotient then multiplied by the number of days in the month prior to the Unit Deactivation Date and (ii) the total monthly revenue requirement after the rate change divided by the number of days in the month of the deactivation, with the quotient then multiplied by the remaining number of days in the month from and including the Unit Deactivation Date.

NRG BUSINESS MARKETING LLC FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF, ORIGINAL VOLUME NO. 2 Reactive Supply and Voltage Control From Generation Sources Service 1. NRG Business Marketing LLC (“NBM”), on behalf of Indian River Power LLC (“Indian River”) and Vienna Power LLC (“Vienna”), provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service (“Reactive Supply Service”) from the generating facilities owned by Indian River and Vienna to PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (“PJM”). This tariff sets forth NBM’s revenue requirement for the provision of Reactive Supply Service to PJM pursuant to PJM’s Open Access Transmission Tariff.
2. NBM’s revenue requirements for the Delmarva zone are set forth below.
Zone Units Annual Revenue Requirement Monthly Revenue Requirement DELMARVA Indian River Unit CT 10 $34,776.00 $2,898.00 Vienna Unit 8 $193,088.16 $16,090.68 Vienna Unit CT 10 $28,358.64 $2,363.22 Total $256,222.80 $21,351.90
PARTIAL MONTH REVENUE REQUIREMENT: When the effective date of this tariff is other than the first day of the month, the revenue requirement shall be a blended revenue requirement for the month of service in which the effective date is set (“Effective Date Month”) as follows: the sum of (i) the total monthly revenue requirement prior to the rate change divided by the number of days in the Effective Date Month, with the quotient then multiplied by the number of days in the Effective Date Month prior to the effective date and (ii) the total monthly revenue requirement after the rate change divided by the number of days in the Effective Date Month, with the quotient then multiplied by the remaining number of days in the Effective Date Month from and including the effective date.

Electric Rate Schedule FERC No. 3 
Reliability Must-Run Rate Schedule
Pursuant to this Reliability Must-Run Rate Schedule (“Rate Schedule”), the Filing Public Utility (“Utility”), on behalf of Indian River Power LLC (“Indian River” or Generation Owner), hereby sets forth the rates, terms, and conditions for Reliability Must-Run (“RMR”) service provided by Indian River Unit 4 (“Unit 4”).
I.	DEFINITIONS
1.1	All capitalized terms used and not defined in Article I or otherwise herein have the meaning set forth in the PJM Governing Documents.
1.2	“Cost of Service Recovery Rate” shall mean the cost of service rate mechanism established pursuant to Section 119 of the PJM Tariff to recover the Cost of Service Recovery Rate components identified in Article V of this Rate Schedule.
1.3	“Service Start Date” shall mean the start date for service pursuant to this Rate Schedule set forth in Section 2.1.
1.4	“FERC” shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or its successor.
1.5	“Incurred” shall mean an expense for Unit 4 which Utility or Generation Owner has become legally obligated to pay, including, but not limited to, instances where Utility/Generation Owner is contractually obligated to make such payment or has received an invoice, bill, or receipt, but has not yet paid the amount due.
1.6	“Indian River” shall mean the entity that will own, operate, and maintain Unit 4 for the purpose of facilitating the reliable operation of the PJM Transmission System.
1.7	“Outage” shall mean a Planned Outage, Maintenance Outage, or Unplanned Forced Outage as defined in PJM Manual 10 (Revision 40), Section 2, or a partial outage/derate as utilized in the PJM Governing Documents.
1.8	“Market Monitor” shall mean the entity acting in the capacity of the Independent Market Monitor for PJM.
1.9	“NERC” shall mean the North American Electric Reliability Corporation.
1.10	“Filing Public Utility” or “Utility,” registered with PJM as a Member pursuant to the terms of the PJM Operating Agreement, shall mean the entity acting as the Designated Agent for the Generation Owner.
1.11	“PJM” shall mean PJM Interconnection, L.L.C.
 
1.12	“PJM Governing Documents” shall mean the PJM Tariff, the PJM Operating Agreement, the PJM Reliability Assurance Agreement, and the PJM Manuals.
1.13	“PJM Manuals” shall mean PJM’s manuals that document PJM’s administrative, planning, operating, and accounting procedures.
1.14	“PJM Operating Agreement” shall mean the Amended and Restated Operating Agreement of PJM Interconnection, L.L.C.
1.15	“PJM Reliability Assurance Agreement” shall mean the Reliability Assurance Agreement Among Load Serving Entities in the PJM Region.
1.16	“PJM Tariff” shall mean the Open Access Transmission Tariff of PJM Interconnection, L.L.C.
1.17	“Project Investment” shall mean an investment made to enable Unit 4 to continue operating for the period of time during which PJM has identified a reliability need. Project Investment will include the projects and costs identified in Attachment A, as modified pursuant to the review and approval processes set forth in this Rate Schedule. While third-party labor costs from non-affiliates may be included in the Project Investment, labor costs associated with employees of Utility and its affiliates will not be included.
1.18	“Settlement Net Revenues” shall mean all charges and credits as calculated pursuant to the PJM Governing Documents, net of the marginal costs in excess of the cost-based offers submitted pursuant to Section 4.1.
1.19	“Term” shall mean the term of this Rate Schedule as established under Article II.
1.20	“Unit 4” shall mean Unit 4 of the Indian River Generating Station.
II.	TERM AND FERC FILINGS
2.1	Service Start Date
The start date for service pursuant to the rates, terms, and conditions of this Rate Schedule is June 1, 2022.
2.2	Term of Rate Schedule
Unless extended as provided in Section 2.6, or RMR service is otherwise terminated as provided in Sections 2.3, 2.4, or 2.5, this Rate Schedule shall terminate with respect to the provision of RMR service from Unit 4 on December 31, 2026 (“Term”) but remain in effect subject to Section 2.7.
 
2.3	Utility Termination Rights
Utility may terminate the provision of RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule consistent with the requirements of Section 113.3 of the PJM Tariff.
2.4	Transmission Upgrade Status and PJM Termination Rights
Beginning at least three (3) quarters prior to the projected in-service date for the Delmarva Power & Light Company (“DPL”) transmission projects that will make Unit 4 no longer necessary for RMR service, PJM shall provide to Utility, the Market Monitor, and the list in Section 7.5 monthly updates of (i) the projected in-service date of the DPL transmission projects and (ii) PJM’s projected date for issuance of notice pursuant to this Section 2.4. Promptly upon determining that Unit 4 is no longer necessary for RMR service pursuant to Section 113.3 of the PJM Tariff, PJM shall provide sixty-five (65) days’ advanced written notice of termination to Utility, after which sixty-five (65) day period the RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule shall terminate. In the event of such termination, the applicable Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge component set forth in Section 5.1 shall be reduced by forty (40) percent for the last twenty (20) days for RMR service.
2.5	Other Events of Termination
For the purpose of Section 113.3 of the PJM Tariff, the provision of RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule shall terminate one hundred twenty (120) days after Unit 4 becomes inoperable if PJM and the Market Monitor provide, or are deemed to have provided, Utility with the notice required under Section 5.2(J) declining to approve a Project Investment and Unit 4 is unable to continue operating without such Project Investment. Within ten (10) days after Utility receives, or is deemed to have received, notice declining to approve a Project Investment under Section 5.2(J), Utility shall provide written notice to PJM, the Market Monitor, and FERC of the termination of the RMR service of this Rate Schedule and shall explain why Unit 4 is inoperable without the Project Investment. Such notice is not the notice pursuant to Section 2.8(c). In the event such notice is provided, the Performance Adjustment set forth in Section 5.1 shall not apply.
2.6	Extension by Agreement
If PJM wishes to extend the Term of this Rate Schedule, PJM shall provide at least one hundred eighty (180) days’ written notice to Utility and the intervenors in Docket No. ER22-1539- 000 prior to the date upon which the RMR service of this Rate Schedule would otherwise terminate. Within forty-five (45) days after receipt of PJM’s notice, Utility will notify PJM of whether it will agree to continue operating if permitted to do so. If Utility is so willing, it will provide PJM and the Market Monitor as part of the notification a status update about the potential ability to extend operations, including any additional Project Investment. Within twenty (20) days after receipt of a Utility notification agreeing to continue operations, PJM and Utility shall use reasonable efforts to determine the duration of the extension if still sought by PJM. Such extension shall be subject to Utility filing an amendment to this Rate Schedule for the rates, terms, and conditions of RMR service during the extended term.
 
2.7	Survival of Obligations
(a)	If the provision of RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule is terminated prior to the date identified in Section 2.2 and Utility has not yet recovered costs of operating Unit 4 under the Cost of Service Recovery Rate, which costs were Incurred, Utility shall be entitled to recover all such unrecovered costs with respect to Unit 4, in accordance with this Rate Schedule.
(b)	If the provision of RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule is terminated prior to the date identified in Section 2.2 and Utility has not yet recovered Project Investment Costs, which costs were Incurred, Utility shall be entitled to recover all such costs in accordance with this Rate Schedule.
(c)	If Unit 4 continues to operate beyond the Term, this Rate Schedule shall not terminate until the obligations established in Section 5.3 of this Rate Schedule have been fully satisfied.
(d)	Expiration or termination of the RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule shall not affect Utility’s or PJM’s accrued rights and obligations arising during the Term, including either party’s obligation to make all payments to the other, and this Rate Schedule shall not terminate until all such obligations have been fully satisfied.
2.8	FERC Filings
(a)	Pursuant to Section 119 of the PJM Tariff, Utility shall file this Rate Schedule with FERC.
(b)	If the Term of this Rate Schedule is extended pursuant to Section 2.6, Utility shall file an amendment to this Rate Schedule, reflecting such extension and any changes to the rates, terms, and conditions for such extension, with FERC pursuant to Federal Power Act § 205.
(c)	Subject to the conditions precedent in Section 2.7, Utility shall file a notice of termination pursuant to 18 C.F.R. § 35.15(c).
III.	OBLIGATIONS
3.1	Application of PJM Governing Documents
The operation of Unit 4 consistent with the terms and conditions of this Rate Schedule shall not be deemed inconsistent with the performance obligations identified in Section 121 of the PJM Tariff.
3.2	Scheduling and Dispatch of Unit 4
PJM may schedule and dispatch Unit 4 subject to the operating limitations identified in Section 3.4 and the availability of coal, equipment, parts, and the other inputs to energy production, consisting of, but not limited to, lime, and oil. Utility will endeavor to maintain inventories of the foregoing, consistent with good utility practice, to provide the RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule.
 
3.3	Operation of Unit 4
(a)	Subject to the terms of this Section 3.3, PJM may schedule and dispatch Unit 4 solely to address (i) an identified transmission reliability need, including transmission reliability needs that are the result of transmission maintenance or transmission work to support upgrades, in support of the requirement to operate such transmission facilities within established thermal, voltage and stability limits under Sections 2 and 3 of PJM Manual 3 and when such transmission reliability needs cannot otherwise be met with available economically dispatched generating resources; (ii) a PJM transmission reliability need caused by a system restoration need as described in PJM Manual 36; (iii) a capacity emergency (as described in PJM Manual 13) during which PJM determines that the resources scheduled for an operating day are not sufficient to maintain the appropriate reserve levels for PJM; (iv) any required testing of Unit 4 as set forth in Section 3.3(e); and (v) as described in Section 6.3(a).
(b)	Subject to the Unit 4 operating limitations identified in Section 3.4, Utility shall operate Unit 4 upon receipt of, and consistent with, a scheduling notice and subsequent dispatch notice issued by PJM. Utility does not guarantee that Unit 4 will start or operate at its rated capacity, and Utility does not guarantee the availability of Unit 4 in response to a PJM scheduling or dispatch notice.
(c)	In its sole discretion, Utility shall not be obligated to cause Unit 4 to be operated in a manner that will cause it to violate the terms of any environmental restrictions or any operating permit limitations.
(d)	PJM shall not issue a scheduling or dispatch notice to Utility for operation of Unit 4 during periods when Unit 4 is unavailable due to an Outage, provided that Utility shall notify PJM of Unit Outages consistent with the PJM Governing Documents.
(e)	Utility, with advance notice of at least one (1) day to, and prior approval by, PJM, may self-schedule Unit 4 under limited circumstances where PJM’s dispatch of Unit 4 is not expected to allow necessary operational activities to occur. These activities generally include, but are not limited to, scheduling Unit 4 to conduct mandatory compliance testing, diagnostic evaluations performed to maintain Unit 4’s ability to operate, and addressing the coal inventory requirements and coal inventory reduction obligations set forth in this Rate Schedule. PJM shall provide compensation pursuant to this Rate Schedule consistent with that provided during a PJM dispatch relating to such periods of operation.
(f)	Utility shall maintain weather preparation measures for Unit 4 for winter and summer seasons consistent with good utility practice. Upon request and with ten (10) Business Days’ notice, PJM may conduct an on-site summer and/or winter readiness inspection of Unit 4 up to two times per year to determine compliance with winter and/or summer performance preparation criteria consistent with good utility practice and, in the case of winter preparation criteria, consistent with PJM Manual 14D. PJM may, at its discretion, develop an inspection report. Should the inspection report identify any discrepancies with the criteria, Utility shall develop a plan to cure such discrepancy within thirty (30) Business Days of the report. If Utility’s efforts to cure the discrepancy are declared deficient by PJM, Utility may provide notice pursuant to Section 2.3.
 
(g)	If Unit 4 has not run for the prior thirty (30) days consecutively, then at the discretion of Utility, and with prior notice to PJM, Unit 4 may self-schedule to operate for up to forty-eight (48) hours. If Unit 4 has not run for the prior thirty (30) days consecutively, PJM may, with prior notice to Utility, schedule Unit 4 to operate for up to forty-eight (48) hours. PJM shall provide compensation pursuant to this Rate Schedule consistent with that provided during a PJM dispatch relating to such periods of operation.
3.4	Operating Restrictions
(a)	Unit 4 shall be subject to its Parameter-Limited Schedule in place with PJM as of the Effective Date; provided, however, to the extent Unit 4 experiences a physical operational limitation that prevents it from meeting such Parameter-Limited Schedule, Utility will modify the parameters to reflect the limitation and will notify PJM via email and eDart as soon as the need for the change is recognized.
(b)	To the extent that Unit 4 offers Synchronized Reserve Service, the parameters for those offers will comply with the PJM Governing Documents.
IV.	MARKET OPERATIONS

4.1	Obligation to Offer Unit 4 into Markets
(a)	Unit 4 shall not be subject to any must-offer obligation in the PJM capacity market. Unit 4 will submit cost-based offers of energy in the PJM Interchange Energy Market in accordance with the PJM Operating Agreement, Schedule 2, Section 1, and PJM Manual 15; provided, however, such offers shall exclude (i) replacement and opportunity costs and (ii) Emissions Costs, as defined in Section 5.4. Unit 4 will be offered with a status of ‘unavailable’ in the Market but will be available to be scheduled pursuant to Section 3.3. The cost-based offer of energy also applies to dispatch pursuant to Section 3.3(e). From FERC’s approval of a Settlement Agreement without modification pertaining to this Rate Schedule, or if parties to the Settlement Agreement agree to accept FERC-proposed modifications, Utility will not include the Maintenance Adder (as defined in the PJM Operating Agreement) in Utility’s cost-based offers for Unit 4 during the Term.
(b)	Except when Unit 4 is unavailable due to an Outage, Unit 4 may be offered based on its cost-based schedule into the Synchronized Reserve market when Unit 4 is otherwise dispatched for reliability. Such cost-based bids shall be calculated in accordance with Section 1.10.1A(j) of the PJM Operating Agreement.
(c)	Except when Unit 4 is unavailable due to an Outage, Unit 4 will provide reactive power consistent with the available capability of the unit and voltage schedules provided for in the relevant interconnection agreement.
 
V.	COMPENSATION FOR RMR SERVICE

Pursuant to Section 119 of the PJM Tariff, Utility shall recover the costs of operating Unit 4 during the Term through the Cost of Service Recovery Rate composed of the (i) charges identified in Section 5.1 and (ii) reimbursements identified in Sections 5.2 and 5.4.
5.1	Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge and Performance Adjustment
Each month during the Term of this Rate Schedule, PJM shall pay to Utility the Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge component as stated:

	Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge
June 1, 2022 – End of Term	$4,150,000.00

Payment of the Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge will be subject to the Performance Adjustment defined and set forth in Attachment B.
5.2	Reimbursement of Project Investment Costs 
Each month during the Term of this Rate Schedule, PJM shall pay to Utility a monthly payment to reimburse the costs of Project Investment undertaken pursuant to this Rate Schedule (“Monthly Project Investment Tracker Payment”). The Monthly Project Investment Tracker Payment shall be calculated in accordance with the following equation:

 
Monthly Project Investment Tracker Payment
 
=	Actual PI Costs accrued
 

 
Where:
 


A	“Project Calendar Year” shall mean the calendar year (i) in which Project Investment is scheduled as set forth in Attachment A hereto, beginning with 2022, and (ii) for which New Project Investment is added. Every September (or another month as mutually agreed upon by Utility, PJM, and the Market Monitor) during the Term beginning in September 2023, Utility, PJM, and the Market Monitor shall perform a review of the status of Project Investment. After this review process, Utility will provide an updated Attachment A (including any revisions) (“Updated Attachment A”) to the list in Section 7.5. Additionally, to the extent possible, the updated Attachment A will include an estimate of when the Project Investment costs for the following year are expected to be included on the invoices referenced in Section 6.1.
B	“Project Investment” shall have the meaning defined in Section 1.17.
C	“Project Investment Costs” shall mean the estimated costs of the Project Investments identified by Project Calendar Year in Attachment A hereto as well as New Project Investment Costs.
D	“New Project Investment” shall mean any Project Investment not listed in
 
Attachment A hereto.
E	“New Project Investment Costs” shall mean costs for New Project Investment.
F	“Actual PI Costs” shall mean the actual Project Investment costs accrued in the calendar month regardless of the Project Calendar Year to which Project Investment is assigned. Actual costs for Project Investment accrued prior to June 1, 2022, for Project Investment for the 2022 Project Calendar Year is Actual PI Costs to be reimbursed pursuant to Article VI.
G	As part of the monthly Excel version of the Utility monthly invoice issued pursuant to Section 6.1 (“Audit Invoice”), starting with the January 2024 invoice, Utility will provide to PJM and the Market Monitor all vendor invoices of $10,000 and above associated with the Project Investment projects included each month (“PI Audit Support Process”). Because accrual accounting entries in an Audit Invoice will be reversed and replaced with vendor invoice costs in subsequent Audit Invoices, such subsequent vendor invoices will be subject to the PI Audit Support Process. The PI Audit Support Process is limited solely to identification of accounting errors, meaning confirming the invoicing ties into the detailed transactions provided as part of the Audit Invoice and, accordingly, will not include questioning the justification for the Project Investment that is reflected in Attachment A and any New Project Investment incurred pursuant to Section 5.2(J). PJM and the Market Monitor will have up to thirty (30) days to review and communicate any identified errors or discrepancies. Utility will then have up to thirty (30) days to address these concerns upon receipt so that any errors are corrected in a subsequent billing month or, if not resolved in that period, the resolution of the identified errors or discrepancies shall be subject to Section 5.2(K).
H	For Project Investments planned for Unit 4 other than those projects identified in Paragraph C, above, for any period after the initial Term that the Rate Schedule remains in effect with respect to Unit 4, Utility shall file with FERC for informational purposes a list of planned Project Investments and costs, with appropriate support, by not later than forty-five (45) days prior to the expiration of the current Term; provided, however, that, if such Term is extended within forty- five (45) days prior to the expiration of the then-current Term, Utility shall file such list of planned Project Investments and costs with appropriate support as soon as practicable after such extension.
I	If the total of the Project Investment costs to be accrued for the Project Calendar Year are expected to exceed the Project Investment Costs identified in Paragraph C, above, or in a list of planned Project Investments and costs filed with FERC pursuant to Paragraph H, above, for which costs will be accrued in that Project Calendar Year by ten percent (10%), Utility shall file a report with PJM, and contemporaneously provide a copy to the Market Monitor, with appropriate support of the reasons for the cost increase, notifying PJM of the additional costs. Utility will provide a copy to the list in Section 7.5. Any such additional Project Investment costs shall be added to the Actual PI Costs.
 
J	If it is necessary to undertake New Project Investment to enable Unit 4 to continue to operate during the remaining Term, and the cost of each New Project Investment is expected to be in excess of $25,000, Utility shall notify and consult with PJM and the Market Monitor in writing, and provide detailed support to identify the nature of the New Project Investment and the expected duration and New Project Investment Costs (“New PI Support”). The New PI Support will be distributed to the list in Section 7.5 when provided to PJM and the Market Monitor. Within fifteen (15) days of receipt of Utility’s notice, PJM and the Market Monitor shall notify Utility in writing of the need to undertake the New Project Investment to support the reliable operation of the PJM Transmission System. During the fifteen
(15) day-time period, the Performance Adjustment set forth in Section 5.1 shall not apply. If PJM and the Market Monitor notify Utility that they decline to approve such New Project Investment, then no New Project Investment will be undertaken and Utility may provide notice pursuant to Section 2.3. If within twenty (20) days of receipt of Utility’s written notice with respect to a New Project Investment, PJM and the Market Monitor fail to notify Utility in writing whether they approve or decline to approve such New Project Investment, PJM and the Market Monitor will be deemed to have provided Utility notice declining to approve such New Project Investment and Utility may provide notice pursuant to Section 2.3. In the event such notice is provided, the Performance Adjustment set forth in Section 5.1 shall not apply. Utility shall not be required to provide notice in advance of any New Project Investment with a cost not expected to exceed $25,000, but, as soon as practicable after deciding to initiate the project, will provide notice to PJM, the Market Monitor, and to the list in Section 7.5 (“New PI Notice”). The New PI Notice will include the estimated New Project Investment Costs and an explanation of the need for the New Project Investment. New Project Investments undertaken in accordance with this Paragraph J shall be added to the Actual PI Costs when accrued.
K	Project Investment costs shall be recovered on the basis of accrued costs. Not later than within ninety (90) days from the end of a Project Calendar Year and, if the end of the Term is not the end of a Project Calendar Year (“Partial Calendar Year”), the end of the Term, Utility will file a report with PJM, and contemporaneously provide a copy to the Market Monitor and to the list in Section 7.5, showing the actual amounts expended for the projects in a Project Calendar Year and, if applicable, the Partial Calendar Year, pursuant to this Rate Schedule. Not later than sixty (60) days after submission of the report to PJM and the Market Monitor at the end of the Term, Utility will refund any amount by which the reimbursed Actual PI Costs exceed actual amounts expended or will charge PJM any amount by which actual expenditures exceed the amount of the Actual PI Costs previously reimbursed to Utility. Any dispute between Utility and PJM, or between Utility and the Market Monitor, concerning the amounts of any over- or under-recoveries shall be subject to the dispute resolution procedure set forth in the PJM Tariff.
5.3	Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement – Continued Operations
In the event that Project Investment enables Unit 4 to remain operational beyond the Term,
 
Utility shall refund to PJM a share of the amount of any Project Investment for which it received reimbursement pursuant to this Rate Schedule as set forth in this Section 5.3. The Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement shall be determined using the following formula:
Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement = (The amount of a Project Investment/Number of months the Project Investment permits Unit 4 to operate) * (Number of months the Project Investment permits Unit 4 to operate – the number of months during the Term in which the Project Investment was placed in-service.
Where:
A.	The number of months the Project Investment permits Unit 4 to operate is determined by the Generation Owner and verified by PJM.
B.	Utility shall make the Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement each month for the number of months a Project Investment permits Unit 4 to continue to operate beyond the Term and shall be credited to transmission customers in such month on the same basis as costs are allocated under Section 120 of the PJM Tariff, for as many months as Unit 4 continues to operate beyond the Term of this Rate Schedule.
This Section 5.3 shall be interpreted in a manner consistent with Section 118 of the PJM Tariff except for the substitution “of the number of months during the Term in which the Project Investment was placed in-service” for “the number of months during the Term” in the Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement equation, above. To assist in such interpretation, the following examples illustrate the correct application of this Section 5.3:

Formula Component	Variable	Example 1	Example 2	Example 3
Project Investment (PI) cost	X	$500,000	$500,000	$500,000
Number of Months PI permits Unit 4 to Operate	Y	60	90	60
The number of months of the Term (excluding Section 2.7 obligations)	Z	54	54	48
The number of months during the Term the PI was in-service	W	4	4	4
Number of months the PI allows Unit 4 to continue to operate past the end of the Term of this Rate Schedule	Y-W	56	86	56
Monthly Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement	X/Y	$8,333	$5,556	$8,333
Months of Project Reimbursement	Y-W	56	86	56

5.4.	Reimbursement of Fuel and Variable Operations and Maintenance Costs
Each month during the Term, PJM shall reimburse, and Utility shall recover, the cost-based amount for the services provided pursuant to Section 4.1 (“Cost-Based Revenue Reimbursement”) and emissions costs (“Emissions Costs”). Emissions Costs, invoiced pursuant to Section 6.1, shall mean the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative (“RGGI”) allowance costs for each month, calculated by multiplying (i) the actual tons of CO2 emitted by Unit 4 for which allowances must
 
be purchased for the emissions by (ii) the market price for such allowances on the last day of the operating month, which market prices are established for January of the year following the operating year. By the first day of each quarter, beginning on June 1, 2022, PJM shall provide a fuel advisory forecast to Utility with the anticipated level of dispatch of Unit 4 for the next twelve (12) months on a monthly basis (the “Advisory Forecast”). Except as set forth in Section 6.3(a), Utility will endeavor to inventory coal based on the Advisory Forecast, with an initial targeted minimum inventory starting at twenty-one (21) days of fuel during the Term. Beginning April 1, 2024, PJM may reduce this initial targeted minimum inventory, on a quarterly basis, based on anticipated levels of dispatch, current fuel inventory levels, and anticipated run times.

VI.	INVOICES AND PAYMENTS

6.1	Utility Monthly Invoicing

Utility will issue a monthly invoice to PJM for the amounts due under Sections 5.1, 5.2, and 5.4 no later than the 15th calendar day of the month following the month in which service is provided, unless extenuating circumstances exist, in which case it will issue the invoice no later than the last business day of the month. Utility will provide a copy to the Market Monitor. Upon request, Utility will provide supporting data to PJM and the Market Monitor for such invoice. Project Investment costs are subject to the true-up process at the end of the Term as set forth in Section 5.2(K). The Performance Adjustment shall be included in the monthly invoice following the calculation performed pursuant to Section 5.1.

6.2	PJM Invoicing
(a)	After PJM receives the monthly invoice pursuant to Section 6.1, PJM will allocate the costs incurred to compensate Utility in accordance with Section 120 of the PJM Tariff. PJM will adjust such monthly invoice by any Settlement Net Revenues received. If such Settlement Net Revenues are less than the monthly invoice submitted pursuant to Section 6.1, PJM will adjust such monthly invoice to account for the differential amount. If the differential amount is less than zero, then the load in the Zone(s) associated with Unit 4 will be charged and Utility will be credited for the differential amount. If such Settlement Net Revenues exceed the monthly invoice submitted pursuant to Section 6.1, PJM will adjust such monthly invoice to a zero value and the differential amount will be credited back to the load in the Zone(s) associated with Unit 4 and charged to Utility. PJM will issue weekly and monthly invoices and issue or collect payments in accordance with Section 14B of the PJM Operating Agreement. Detailed settlement reports are available monthly to view energy revenues received in excess of the cost-based offers pursuant to Section 4.1.

(b)	Pursuant to Section 3.3, Unit 4 operation is limited to providing RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule. Notwithstanding such limitation, in the event there are prospective energy and ancillary services operating revenues received by Unit 4 from PJM markets that commence after the effective date of the Settlement Agreement and that are in addition to the revenue identified in this Rate Schedule (“Unit 4 Incremental Revenue”), such Unit 4 Incremental Revenue net of costs determined consistent with the PJM Operating Agreement Schedule 2, shall
 
be credited back to the load in the Zone(s) associated with Unit 4 and charged to Utility. For clarity, Unit 4 Incremental Revenue does not include any revenues associated with capacity interconnection rights.

6.3	Final Invoicing

(a)	Beginning April 1, 2025, PJM shall endeavor to identify opportunities to direct Utility to reduce fuel inventory levels as soon as reliably practical, based on reasonable anticipation of the expiration of this Rate Schedule. No later than sixty (60) days prior to the expiration of this Rate Schedule, Utility shall inform PJM of inventory levels of fuels and coordinate with PJM to schedule and dispatch Unit 4 to deplete such inventory in a manner that endeavors to minimize the coal inventory costs that are allocated to the load pursuant to Section 120 of the PJM Tariff. If fuel is remaining at the end of the Term, Utility will undertake reasonable commercial efforts to sell such remaining fuel, and PJM will reimburse the actual costs of the fuel and removal costs less the sales price, if any, of the remaining fuel. Utility shall invoice PJM for the removal costs monthly as Incurred. If the inventory costs exceed the resale proceeds received by Utility, then Utility shall invoice PJM for the difference in the month after any resale occurs. Relevant fuels include coal and oil. In the event Utility disposes of fuel inventory prior to the end of the Term, this Section 6.3(a) shall apply to such sale(s) and will be invoiced as accrued or Incurred subject to true up to actuals.

(b)	At the end of the Term, PJM will pay for actual costs and removal costs less the sales price, if any, of the remaining chemicals, bulk lubricating oils and coal combustion by- products (“Consumables”) that were procured, retained, or produced, as applicable, to provide RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule. Utility shall invoice PJM for such costs no later than ninety (90) days from the end of the Term. In the event Utility disposes of chemicals or bulk lubricating oils inventory (“Input Consumables”) prior to the end of the Term, this Section 6.3(b) shall apply to such sale(s) and will be invoiced as accrued or Incurred subject to true up to actuals. The coal combustion by-products, which exclude the landfills, may or may not be sold.
(c)	Except as otherwise provided in Section 5.1, Section 5.2(K), and Attachment B, not later than ninety (90) days from the end of the Term, Utility will issue final invoices for amounts due under this Rate Schedule. However, notwithstanding any provision of this Rate Schedule to the contrary, should costs Incurred to provide RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule continue to be Incurred after the end of the Term, or should fuel inventory or Consumables take longer to liquidate, the final invoices shall be due within ninety (90) days from the date cost incurrence ceases or fuel and Consumables are fully liquidated.

(d)	To the extent there are sales revenues in excess of the cost of the fuel and Consumables and related removal cost, such amounts shall be credited back to the load in the Zone(s) associated with Unit 4 and charged to Utility.
 
6.4	Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement

In the event Section 5.3 will apply, sixty (60) days prior to the end of the Term Utility shall provide the schedule of Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement identifying by month and year each month’s refund amount PJM shall use to comply with Section 5.3.

VII.	MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS

7.1	PJM Governing Documents

Reference to PJM Governing Documents included herein shall be to the version in effect as of the Service Start Date.

7.2	Time Period Waivers

Utility and PJM may mutually agree to waive any of the time periods set forth herein that apply jointly and only to Utility and PJM. Utility, PJM, and the Market Monitor may mutually agree to waive any of the time periods set forth herein that apply jointly and only to Utility, PJM, and the Market Monitor. The dates and time periods in Sections 2.1, 2.2, 2.4, 2.6, and 9.3 may be changed only by Commission acceptance of a filing or filings that are made in accordance with this Rate Schedule.

7.3	Designated Representatives
Except as otherwise expressly provided in this Rate Schedule or required by law, all notices, consents, requests, demands, approvals, authorizations and other communications provided for in this Rate Schedule to Utility and the Generation Owner shall be in writing and shall be sent by email, followed by personal delivery, certified mail, return receipt requested, facsimile transmission, or by recognized overnight courier service, to the intended Party at such Party’s address set forth below. All such notices shall be deemed to have been duly given and to have become effective: (a) upon receipt if delivered in person or by facsimile; (b) two (2) days after having been delivered to a courier for overnight delivery; or (c) seven (7) days after having been deposited in the United States mail as certified or registered mail, return receipt requested, all fees pre-paid, addressed to the applicable addresses set forth below. 7.4	Transfer of this Rate Schedule
In the event of an acquisition of either the membership interests in the Generation Owner or Unit 4 while this Rate Schedule is in effect, this Rate Schedule shall be transferred as part of such acquisition, Utility shall cease to be the Designated Agent for the Generation Owner and Unit 4 for this Rate Schedule, and this Rate Schedule shall be subject to the notice of succession requirements set forth in Section 36.16 of the FERC’s regulations, 18 C.F.R. § 35.16; provided that (i) the acquiror or its affiliate qualify as a PJM Member as defined under the PJM Operating Agreement, Section 11.6 and (ii) the acquiror, its affiliate or a third party retained as a power marketer or energy manager qualify as a PJM Market Participant as defined under the PJM Operating Agreement, Schedule 1, Section 1.4 and meet the credit requirements set forth in the PJM Tariff, Attachment Q.

VIII.	STANDARD OF REVIEW
8.1	Standard of Review

The standard of review for changes to any rate, charge, classification, term or condition of this Rate Schedule proposed by any party to Docket No. ER22-1539 shall solely be the most stringent standard of review set forth in United Gas Pipe Line Co. v. Mobile Gas Service Corp., 350 U.S. 332 (1956) and Federal Power Commission v. Sierra Pacific Power Co., 350 U.S. 348 (1956) and clarified by Morgan Stanley Capital Group, Inc. v. Public Util. Dist. No. 1 of Snohomish, 554 U.S. 527, 128 S. Ct. 2733 (2008) and NRG Power Marketing, LLC, et al. v. Maine Public Utilities Commission, 558 U.S. 165, 130 S.Ct. 693 (2010). The standard of review for changes to any rate, charge, classification, term, or condition of this Rate Schedule proposed under Federal Power Act § 206 by (i) a third-party that did not intervene in Docket No. ER22-1539-000, or (ii) FERC acting sua sponte shall be the statutory just and reasonable standard of review.

IX.	SETTLEMENT
9.1	Interim Rate Filing
This Rate Schedule is revised pursuant to the terms of a settlement agreement (“Settlement Agreement”) in Docket No. ER22-1539-000 that is pending FERC approval. Inter alia, the Settlement Agreement provides for the filing of this Rate Schedule (“Settlement RMR RS”) to be implemented on an interim basis (“Interim RMR RS”) pending FERC action on the Settlement Agreement.
9.2	Conditional
The Interim RMR RS is conditional pursuant to the terms of the Settlement Agreement. Inter alia, the Settlement Agreement provides for reversion to the rates, terms and conditions of the version filed in Docket No. ER22-1539-000 and Docket No. ER23-2688-000, respectively (“Filed RMR RS”), in the event the Settlement Agreement is not approved as filed and the parties to the Settlement Agreement do not agree to accept FERC-proposed modifications to the Settlement Agreement.
9.3	Refund and Credit Review
Consistent with the refund obligation set forth in NRG Power Marketing LLC, 170 FERC
¶ 61,156 at P 43 (2022), the Settlement Agreement provides for refunds if approved or if parties to the Settlement Agreement agree to accept FERC-proposed modifications to the Settlement Agreement. PJM will effectuate such refunds within sixty (60) days of a final, non-appealable FERC order accepting the Settlement Agreement. No later than upon the filing of the Settlement Agreement, PJM shall take into account Utility’s refund obligation for purposes of determining Utility’s credit obligations under PJM Tariff, Attachment Q.
9.4	Effectiveness of Revised Rates, Terms, and Conditions
Unless specifically indicated otherwise in this Rate Schedule, the revised rates, terms, and conditions set forth in the Settlement RMR RS shall apply prospectively from the effective date of
 
the Interim RMR RS. For clarification, application of revised Sections 1.17, 3.2, 5.1, and 5.3 shall be treated effective as of June 1, 2022, and application of the eliminated carrying charges for Project Investment in Section 5.2 of the Filed RMR RS shall be treated effective as of June 1, 2022.

ATTACHMENT B

PERFORMANCE ADJUSTMENT
Beginning January 1, 2024, Unit 4 shall be subject to a performance adjustment comprised of a transmission-based adjustment (“Transmission Performance Adjustment”) and a reliability-based adjustment (“Reliability Performance Adjustment”) (together, “Performance Adjustment”). The Performance Adjustment reflects the portion of fixed costs that are subject to recovery based on Unit 4 performance. The Performance Adjustment will be determined in accordance with the procedures described below:

1.	Transmission Performance Adjustment: PJM will endeavor to notify Utility of the potential need for Unit 4 to operate in support of DPL’s transmission upgrade work ten (10) days prior to the beginning of the first day of that necessary operation (“Transmission Notice”). A Transmission Notice is not a scheduling or a dispatch instruction but an expression of the potential need for Unit 4 to operate to support DPL’s transmission upgrade work during load levels requiring Unit 4’s operation, and will include tentative identification of timing, hours of operation, and levels of operation.
If Unit 4 fails to perform one or more of the days included in the Transmission Notice, such failure will be subject to the Transmission Performance Adjustment, which will be equal to (the annual Fixed-Cost Charge divided by three hundred sixty-five (365)) times the number of days recorded in the tracking account. Each such day that Unit 4 is unavailable or unable to perform in accordance with the Transmission Notice (other than during approved Planned Outages), and, such unavailability is the sole cause for a delay of the planned transmission work as determined by PJM, each day of such delay in the planned transmission work will be recorded in a tracking account; provided that, to the extent Unit 4 is unable to run for certain hours of the operating day but nonetheless performs during some of the hours of the operating day, and PJM determines that such non-performance does not delay the planned transmission work for that day, such day would not be recorded in the tracking account. If the DPL transmission projects are placed into service on or before December 31, 2025, no Transmission Performance Adjustment will apply.
2.	Reliability Performance Adjustment: Unit 4 is expected to operate if called upon by PJM to maintain grid reliability, as set forth in Section 3.3(a)(ii)-(iii) of this Rate Schedule. In the event Unit 4 is unable to operate within the Operating Restrictions set forth in Section 3.4 of this Rate Schedule, and if this failure to operate occurs coincident with an Emergency, as defined below, Unit 4 will be assessed an hourly adjustment calculated as the positive difference between Unit 4’s dispatched hourly MW output and Unit 4’s actual hourly MW output multiplied by $150, provided that no adjustment will be assessed if Unit 4’s actual hourly MW output is within twelve percent (12%) of the dispatched hourly MW output. For the Reliability Performance Adjustment “Emergency” is defined as any emergency action in the DPL Zone for capacity shortages that initiates a Voltage Reduction Warning, Voltage Reduction Action, Manual Load Dump Warning, or Manual Load Dump Action.
 
2 of 2

3.	If Utility receives a Transmission Notice and is dispatched to support DPL’s transmission upgrade work and an Emergency occurs, the higher of the Reliability Performance Adjustment or the Transmission Performance Adjustment will apply.

4.	The total of all Transmission Performance Adjustments and Reliability Performance Adjustments that are assessed to Unit 4 within a calendar year shall not exceed $4.0 million.

5.	In the event of termination of RMR service prior to December 31, 2026, there will be no Transmission Performance Adjustment or Reliability Performance Adjustment applied to Unit 4’s performance during the sixty-five (65) day notice period under Section 2.4 of this Rate Schedule, but any assessment of either Performance Adjustment shall continue into the sixty-five (65) day notice period under Section 2.4 of this Rate Schedule or following termination of RMR service as necessary to ensure full recovery, subject to the annual cap set forth in Section 4 of this Attachment B.

6.	Notwithstanding the foregoing rates, terms, and conditions for each Performance Adjustment, neither Performance Adjustment will apply for those periods where Unit 4’s inability to perform in whole or in part is the result of (i) degraded coal quality in the last sixty (60) days of the Term or (ii) insufficient coal inventory in response to PJM compliance with Section 5.4 and Section 6.3(a).
